<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Gonzalez and Dad Reunited
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez was back in his father's
arms Saturday after federal agents used battering rams and pepper spray to
hustle him from Miami and the relatives fighting to block his return to Cuba.
The boy's Miami relatives arrived in Washington to try and see the boy. Crying
with fright, the 6-year-old Cuban boy was taken before dawn and flown to Andrews
Air Force Base outside Washington, where he was in seclusion with his father,
stepmother and baby half-brother. Though in his father's custody, Elian's fate
still remains unsettled. The courts will ultimately rule on whether the boy
should remain in the United States.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
260 Arrested in Miami; Cubans Celebrate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- More than 260 people were arrested and more than 207 fires were
set Saturday by protesters on the streets of Little Havana after Elian Gonzalez
was snatched away by federal agents. Riot police with batons and shields beat
down demonstrators who set bonfires and uprooted concrete benches. In Cuba,
Fidel Castro declared Saturday a day of truce between the United States and
Cuba, praising U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and INS officials for reuniting
Elian Gonzalez with his father. About 400,000 people were called to a historic
sugar refinery to celebrate the breakthrough in the personal and political drama
that has gripped the island for five months.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miami Kin Try To See Elian, Dad
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez followed him to
Washington Saturday, hoping to keep the 6-year-old boy from going back to Cuba.
They were turned away from the air base gate behind which Elian was reunited
with his father. The group attempted to hold a news conference outside Andrews
Air Force, but gave up amid a crush of protesters and news media, saying only
that they would make another attempt to see Elian and his Cuban father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, on Sunday. The group included Lazaro Gonzalez, who has cared
for the boy in his house for the five months since Elian's rescue at sea; cousin
Marisleysis Gonzalez, and the fisherman who rescued him, Donato Dalrymple.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
L.A. Janitors Reach Tentative Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The union representing striking janitors reached a
tentative contract agreement Saturday night with 18 cleaning companies,
negotiators for both sides said. However, the 8,500 janitors will continue their
nearly three-week-old walkout until they vote on the proposed deal Monday, union
President Mike Garcia said. Officials for both sides refused to release details
pending the ratification vote but said they were pleased with the proposal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China Chicken Factory Fire Kills 38
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A fire Saturday in a chicken processing factory in eastern
China killed at least 38 workers and injured 20, the state-run Xinhua News
Agency said. The fire broke out Saturday morning, when around 240 workers were
in the factory in Qingzhou, in coastal Shandong province, Xinhua said in a
report late Saturday. The fire took nearly two hours to extinguish and its cause
is now being investigated, Xinhua said. It gave no other details.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Planes Crash in Va.; 7 Dead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORTON, Va. (AP) -- Five members of a family were found dead in the wreckage
of a small plane in the hills of southwestern Virginia Saturday, more than a day
after the plane disappeared from radar, officials said. The single-engine Mooney
20G aircraft was en route from Nashville, Tenn., to Roanoke when it vanished
from radar late Friday morning near Norton. The cause of the crash was not
immediately known, but Virginia State Trooper Dan Helton said initial
investigations suggest the plane was flying too low and hit several tree tops
before going down. Also today, two people were killed when a small airplane
crashed in Shenandoah County in northwest Virginia, state police said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
DiCaprio-Clinton Interview Short
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- After all the fuss, actor Leonardo DiCaprio's 20-minute chat
in the White House with President Clinton about global warming was edited down
to two minutes on ABC's Saturday special, ''Planet Earth 2000.'' DiCaprio was
seen asking the president three questions. The interview prompted a flood of
criticism from people -- including some within ABC News -- who wondered why the
hunky ''Titanic'' star was being sent to do a journalist's job. DiCaprio is
chairman of the Earth Day 2000 celebration committee and approached ABC with the
idea of a special on global warming.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
76ers Defeat Hornets 92-82 in Playoffs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Allen Iverson scored a career playoff-high 40 points
Saturday night, getting 15 of them in a seven-minute burst in the third quarter
as the Philadelphia 76ers beat Charlotte 92-82 in Game 1 of their playoff
series. Iverson surpassed his previous playoff-high of 37 reached last year
against Orlando.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
</TEXT>
