<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Defector Baez Wins First Game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- Danys Baez, the Cuban pitcher who
defected during last year's Pan American Games, earned his first
minor league victory Saturday night as Kinston defeated
Winston-Salem 6-1 in the Carolina League.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3 right-hander allowed only one run on three hits. He
struck out six in seven innings to record his first win in four
starts with the Cleveland Indians' Single-A affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was by far his best outing,'' Kinston manager Brad
Komminsk said. ''Everything was working for him. He had good
command of his breaking pitches, his fastball and changeup. He went
after the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The only run against the 22-year-old Baez came in the fifth on
two singles and a ground out. In the sixth, he made short work of
potential trouble -- retiring three straight hitters after a leadoff
triple.
</P>
<P>
   Baez, speaking through an interpreter, said his control and
mechanics were sound.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched for the Cuban National Team and defected while
playing in the Pan Am games in Canada. The Indians signed Baez to a
$14.5 million, four-year contract last November. Baez is ranked by
Baseball America as the No. 2 prospect in the Cleveland
organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
