<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 04:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Janitors Reach Tentative Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A tentative contract agreement has been
reached to end a nearly three-week-old janitors' strike, though
workers won't return to their jobs until the deal is ratified, a
union official said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached Saturday night, after about seven
hours of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   A ratification vote was scheduled set for Monday, three weeks to
the day that 8,500 janitors walked off the job throughout Los
Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for both sides refused to release details pending the
vote, but pronounced themselves pleased with the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Garcia, president of Service Employees International Union
Local 1877, said he hopes the janitors approve the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good deal, but we can't comment more than that,''
Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Davis, a chief negotiator for the cleaning companies, said
unionized janitors could be back on the job as early as Monday
night if the contract is approved.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a decent deal for both sides,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies had been using replacement workers since April 3, when
the janitors walked struck against 18 cleaning contractors who
handle most of the city's commercial properties.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reached Saturday was with nine contractors that
handle 97 percent of the affected buildings, Davis said. The other
firms are small and are expected to agree to any deal struck, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The janitors generally earn between $6.80 and $7.90, and were
seeking wage increases of $1-an-hour per year for each of the next
three years. Contractors had offered more modest raises.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's talks were the first held since last Wednesday, when
negotiations broke off with both sides only a nickel apart on
wages.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said some property owners worked behind the scenes to
encourage both sides to settle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think a little give and take with both sides'' led to
agreement, he said. ''It's been a tough strike for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The first week of the strike was marked by a series of ''rolling
strikes'' in which janitors shut down more and more buildings as
each day went by. Wearing red T-shirts and hoisting ''Justice for
Janitors'' signs, they marched through downtown streets, blocked
busy intersections, held candlelight vigils.
</P>
<P>
   They also staged mass protests that stopped traffic around
high-rises and office buildings in West Los Angeles and neighboring
Beverly Hills. Sympathy strikes were staged in New York, Chicago
and other cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 0416 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000423.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrest Made in N.M. Pilgrim Deaths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALCALDE, N.M. (AP) -- A man was arrested early Sunday and charged
with murder in the deaths of two teen-agers killed during a Good
Friday pilgrimage to a church where thousands of people hope for
miracles.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Herrera, 19, of Espanola, was arrested at a friend's home
in Alcalde around 2:40 a.m., said state police Sgt. Royleen
Ross-Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   She said Herrera was an acquaintance of the 17-year-olds
shooting victims, Richard Martinez and Karen Castanon, but did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was found lying on a highway before daybreak Friday
about 30 miles north of Santa Fe. Castanon, his girlfriend, was
found several miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers were among thousands of pilgrims making the
annual spiritual trek to the Santuario de Chimayo, a small Roman
Catholic church in the tiny village of Chimayo that is said to
contain healing dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Ross-Weaver said the arrest was made after police made a public
appeal for help and received a phone tip. ''We were able to develop
the suspect and we also have physical evidence linking him to the
crime,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 200 years, pilgrims have journeyed to Chimayo to
visit the church. Last year, an estimated 65,000 people visited the
church during Holy Week.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the church, in a room next to the sanctuary, is a
small hole with dirt thought to possess healing power. Left nearby
are crutches, canes and rosaries left by believers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 1116 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000423.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Work of Cancer Cells Studied  </HEADLINE>
By VICKIE CHACHERE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Cancer researchers sometimes liken their work
to wandering through a forest of genetic material hoping to find
the paths that lead to better diagnosis, treatments and possibly
cures.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers at the H. Lee Moffitt Cancer Center and Research
Institute have a new high-tech guide for their journey. They are
using a machine called a DNA microarray that can scan the thousands
of genes in a cancer cell at one time and point out new paths to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Moffitt doctors said research that took them 10 years to conduct
can now be accomplished in a single afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great new stuff,'' said Jack Pledger, associate center
director for basic research. ''It's at the forefront of cancer
research.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moffitt effort is part of a $4.1 million National Cancer
Institute project that established microarray laboratories in 24
institutions nationwide. The Moffitt laboratory is the only one the
NCI awarded for Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The microarray is actually a collection of machines and
computers that can take the genetic material of a cancer cell, copy
it onto a computer chip and scan it into a computer that compares
the diseased cell to a healthy one.
</P>
<P>
   In vivid green, blue and fuchsia dots the machine highlights
differences for researchers to further explore.
</P>
<P>
   Pledger said as scientists learn more about the molecular basis
of cancer, they eventually hope to further distinguish between
different types of cancer that attack the same part of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they hope that will make for more accurate diagnosis
of the disease, aid in the development of new drugs that target the
damaged DNA and improve the treatment decisions patients and their
doctors make, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be doing a better job of diagnosis,'' said Lou Stoudt,
a National Cancer Institute senior investigator who oversees a
microarray project in Bethesda, Md. ''We will be rewriting the text
books on cancer diagnosis and giving cancer a molecular diagnosis
instead of just what it looks like under the microscope.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its high-tech promise, the microarray appears as a
humble-looking collection of machines. One resembles an office
copier, another looks strangely like a rotisserie cooker.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-hour process begins with researchers extracting the
genetic material from a cancer cell, transferring its image to a
slide that can be read by the computer that does the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Moffitt keeps a library of computer chips that store all the
known genes and some unknown genes from healthy cells to use for
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   On a computer screen, researchers can clearly see the healthy
and diseased cells line up next to each other, the differences
between them apparent. Whether the abnormalities the researchers
can see in the cancer cell is exactly what's causing it to grow out
of control requires further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Deepak Agrawal, scientific director of Moffitt's microarray lab,
said the machine doesn't do all the work for researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 100,000 genes in a human cell, scientists know the
function of only about 7,000. But that body of knowledge is
expanding under the Human Genome project in which scientists hope
to map all of the body's genes.
</P>
<P>
   The NCI's Stoudt said the microarray has created entirely new
opportunities for cancer exploration that didn't exist a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''You wouldn't do this work without these machines,'' he said.
''We in molecular biology have looked at one or two or three genes
at a time. Here on our microarrays we look at 18,500 genes at a
time. It gives you sort of a birds-eye view of the workings of a
cancer cell that hadn't been seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors eventually hope to expand the use of microarrays to
other genetic diseases, particularly those of the immune system
like lupus.
</P>
<P>
   Pledger said he hopes the microarray might lead doctors to the
answers of some of a patient's most difficult questions about
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why do some people smoke a pack a day and never get lung
cancer and some people never smoke and do? Why does chemotherapy
work for some people and not for others?'' he asked. ''We don't
know. This kind of machinery, this is what will do it for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 1201 </TRAILER>
