<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sands Drift From N.C. State Park  </HEADLINE>
By MELINDA DESLATTE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) -- Jockey's Ridge State Park, the tallest
sand dune on the Atlantic Coast and one of the most extraordinary,
natural, living wonders in the world, has a unique problem: It
won't stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Strong winds are pushing the 419-acre park steadily south at a
rate of 3 feet to 6 feet each year. Three hurricanes since last
August reshaped the dune, which swallowed a miniature golf course,
migrated 600 feet in some areas and routinely spills onto back
yards and driveways.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials want to preserve the dune because it provides a
habitat for a variety of plants, wild game, birds and rodents that
can survive the harsh and windy climate. Researchers and park
officials have joined in trying to devise a long-term plan to
corral the shifting sands.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1995, officials asked the public for recommendations.
Five years later, the suggestion box is still open.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here we are trying to manage resources in a park that is
inherently mobile within a fixed boundary,'' said Sue Regier, who
is in charge of the resource management program at the North
Carolina Division of Parks and Recreation.
</P>
<P>
   At about 85 feet in height, Jockey's Ridge contains 10.4 million
cubic yards of sand, enough to fill about six million dump trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Five scientists recently completed a two-year study of the
park's geological history and likely future movement. The
researchers studied when and how the dune formed and how it has
changed. They examined the sand supply, vegetation, wind and
visitor impact.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials say the study will help them better understand
the sand movement so they can contain Jockey's Ridge within its
boundaries, but the options are limited.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey's Ridge, bordered on one side by Roanoke Sound, is the
southernmost in a series of massive dunes extending north to False
Cape, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's over a mile long. I tell people it's visible from the
space shuttle,'' said Marshall Ellis, a resource management
specialist with the park service. ''It's quite a sand pile. It just
won't stay still.''
</P>
<P>
   The park is beginning to encroach on Soundside Road, which
borders the southern end of the dune and is the site of several
homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the trouble spot. That's the cork in the bottle,'' said
Ellis, who has been studying the dune.
</P>
<P>
   When the sand became too serious a threat to six homes, the park
service bought them. A massive pile of sand now occupies the spot
where one house was torn down.
</P>
<P>
   The sand dune was designated a state park in 1975 and is a
popular attraction for hang gliders, campers and anyone with a kite
and an adventurous spirit. Scientists believe the sand originally
came from offshore islands and was transported by strong winds.
</P>
<P>
   But recent storms -- including Hurricanes Dennis, Floyd and Irene
last year alone -- continue to wreak havoc on the dune.
</P>
<P>
   ''This place is pretty fragile. Anything you do has an effect on
it,'' said park superintendent George Barnes. ''It moved a lot
faster because of the storms. The storms really messed us up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, more than 1.2 million people visited the park last
year, and a 25th anniversary celebration is planned for June.
</P>
<P>
   Cola Vaughan co-owns and manages a rental home on the same side
of Soundside Road as Jockey's Ridge. Part of the sand dune looms
over his back yard. When that happened before, he said, the park
service moved the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not terribly concerned. If they do a haul like they did
four or five years ago, that will keep the sand under control,'' he
said. ''They want their sand. It's like owning a dairy farm, and
the cows keep wandering off.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say the dune is losing its height, although the
amount of sand is the same. Once a pointy, 110-foot-tall behemoth,
it now is 25 feet shorter and rounder.
</P>
<P>
   The park service installed fences and bulldozed sand. It bought
the six homes and the land that was the site for the miniature golf
course after the course was swallowed by the dune. Today, the
turrets of a miniature castle poke from the mounds of sand. Barnes
said officials will consider buying other properties if the owners
make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ''(But) we can't keep buying up property. Our neighbors probably
wouldn't want that,'' Regier said. ''We're dealing with them as
willing sellers. We're not actively pursuing them, though the dune
could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Four-foot-tall fences and old Christmas trees placed throughout
the park to catch the sand now are buried in it. Only a few
branches and fence posts are visible.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers and park officials are reviewing countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've basically got three choices,'' Ellis said. ''You can do
nothing, which is not an option, you can haul sand away on a
regular basis, or you can vegetate it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hauling is what we've been doing, but hauling sand is
expensive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regier said 50,000 cubic yards of sand could be moved about
every five years from the park's southern end to the northern end
for recycling back through the dune.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said 40,000 cubic yards of sand were moved in 1994; 8,000
cubic yards in 1996; and 4,000 cubic yards in February. Park
officials are seeking permits to move another 40,000 to 50,000
cubic yards of sand this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Regier said a regular bulldozing program could put the park on a
cycle that might control sand movement without harming the dune.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hauling sand seems to be the only sure decision now,'' Ellis
said. ''Hauling sand is the easy thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Park officials also are considering planting vegetation. The
study shows the dune was stabilized twice that way since its
development, but fire, wind or salt spray destroyed the vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Regier and Ellis warn that anchoring the dune with plants would
defeat the purpose of having an active dune system.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents feel the same way, said Majid Elbers, who lives
at the northern end of the park and is president of the board of
directors for the Friends of Jockey's Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody who has been involved in this project in any way has
(been opposed) to grassing it over,'' she said. ''What's exciting
about the park is the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wright Brothers Memorial in nearby Kill Devil Hills once had
a marching dune, but in the late 1920s, the state stabilized the
dune with grass, and it is now a grassy hill, Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we're going to vegetate (Jockey's Ridge), we're only
talking about this southern end. But the majority of the park, we
would not even consider that,'' he said. ''We acquired the dune
because we wanted to keep it as a naturally functioning dune.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 1202 </TRAILER>
