<HEADLINE> Doctor struggles day-to-day living with brain injury  </HEADLINE>
o0140nyc--
r n AM-NY--BrainInjury Bjt   04-23 0826
AM-NY--Brain Injury, Bjt,0799   
Doctor struggles day-to-day living with brain injury
AP Membership Enterprise, 
By DONNA JACKEL
o0140nyc--
r n AM-NY--BrainInjury Bjt   04-23 0826
AM-NY--Brain Injury, Bjt,0799   
Doctor struggles day-to-day living with brain injury
AP Membership Enterprise
By DONNA JACKEL
Rochester Democrat and Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Dr. Claudia L. Osborn teaches medical
students, but when she goes to the post office to mail a letter,
she sometimes mails her car keys by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   She is an excellent cook, but before beginning the task, she
must draw diagrams of exactly how she will prepare the food.
</P>
<P>
   And when she gets behind the wheel to drive, a little beeper on
her wrist goes off every three minutes to remind her to look at a
note on the dashboard, which states her destination.
</P>
<P>
   Osborn, author of ''Over My Head: A Doctor's Own Story of Head
Injury from the Inside Looking Out,'' is visiting Rochester on
Wednesday to talk about learning to live with a head injury.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago at age 33, Osborn was director of residency
training at two Detroit hospitals and a professor at Michigan State
University's College of Osteopathic Medicine. That all ended when
she went for a bike ride without wearing a helmet and was struck by
a car.
</P>
<P>
   Some initial symptoms -- difficulty speaking and understanding
others -- eventually improved. But she had permanent weakness to her
right side and damaged short-term memory.
</P>
<P>
   Most devastating was the loss of ''executive function,'' the
ability to carry out more than one task at a time. This left her
easily distracted and unable to generate ideas, organize thoughts
or make plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't do much of anything,'' Osborn said. ''I was told
over and over that I had a brain injury, but I had no way to absorb
that information. I couldn't perceive that anything was different
because my brain wasn't telling me it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborn insisted upon returning to work seven weeks after the
accident. When she forgot to look at a patient's X-ray, which could
have jeopardized the patient's life, Osborn was so shaken that she
went to a neurologist, who told her not to work until she received
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   In the hope of regaining her career, she spent 18 months at the
Head Trauma Program at the Rusk Institute of Rehabilitation
Medicine at New York University Medical Center in Manhattan. A few
months into the program, she began to realize the extent of her
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a sense of overwhelming devastation,'' she said. ''I
couldn't imagine living a life without medicine or how limited my
life had become.''
</P>
<P>
   Her injury also left her adynamic, which meant she spoke in a
monotone and had poor eye contact and little facial expression. By
watching tapes of herself, she learned how to become more animated
and ''eventually started to feel some of those emotions again.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a coach who was ''very good at instilling
hope,'' she learned how to use ''memory props'' to compensate for
the parts of her brain that no longer functioned. She maintained a
notebook containing her daily activities and placed cue cards
around the house instructing her how to carry out simple daily
tasks, like brushing her teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, her props are more sophisticated. She uses a portable
computer instead of a notebook and carries a digital recording
device to remind her to perform tasks. For example, when she lets
her dog out, she records a message, ''Let Mike back in in 20
minutes.'' Twenty minutes later, the recording goes off, reminding
her to do so.
</P>
<P>
   A second beeper goes off every 15 minutes, reminding her to
check her daily planner.
</P>
<P>
   This way of life is as exhausting as it sounds. ''By the end of
the day you can't have a very good conversation with her,'' said
her mother, Jeanne Findlater of Naples, Fla. ''She tires more
easily mentally and tries to work several breaks into her day.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Osborn seven years to write her book, but she said it is
her proudest achievement. She now spends much of her time on the
lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling alone, she likens her first trips to I Love Lucy
episodes, where misunderstandings keep rippling until they are out
of control. If Osborn checked her bags at the ticket counter, went
to the bathroom and then forgot to set her alarm, she might become
disoriented. Instead of waiting for her flight, she'd return to her
car.
</P>
<P>
   ''The parking attendant knows me and tells me, 'You just arrived
half an hour a go, do you think you really want to leave?'''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Osborn will be the first to tell you that the person she
was before the accident no longer exists. But she has learned to
develop her strengths -- her writing and teaching abilities.
</P>
<P>
   She is an associate clinical professor of medicine at Michigan
State University. And through her public appearances, Osborn tries
to impart to others with brain injuries what she has learned.
</P>
<P>
   ''The acceptance of self is essential if anyone is going to make
it -- the ability to move forward instead of sitting there and
remembering the old person you used to be,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
