<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Clinton, Gore Raise Cash  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Politics makes strange bedfellows, but the
trio of politicians sharing the spotlight Monday night has some
truly bizarre dynamics. For the first time this political season,
President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and first lady-cum-Senate
candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton are to appear side by side at a
fund-raising party in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The president is keenly interested in seeing Gore elected as his
successor. Clinton is also the game political spouse these days,
offering encouragement and a little behind-the-scenes strategizing
to his wife, the rookie Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the vice president took pains to distance
himself from the scandal-tinged boss. He has made several political
solo flights, including a break with the White House over the Elian
Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, charting her extraordinary role reversal from
helpmate to candidate, has also kept her political distance from
man who is both her husband and her party's top fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was a silent partner during his wife's formal campaign
announcement in February, and her campaign still refers to her
simply as ''Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that bothers Clinton, who shares fundamental political
beliefs with his vice president and wife, aides say.
</P>
<P>
   ''He recognizes that they will have different points of view
from time to time, but on the big things ... they all see pretty
much eye to eye,'' said White House spokesman Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a one-man money-making machine for Democrats, gives
two, four, sometimes eight fund-raising speeches a week now. He
never misses an opportunity to tout Gore's candidacy. He also
mentions his wife's Senate bid frequently, often with a joke about
his own aspirations to join ''the Senate spouses' club.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not running for anything,'' he says in nearly every
speech. He drew an affectionate laugh from a partisan audience in
Atlanta this month when he added: ''Most days, I'm OK with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Graff, a political science professor at Columbia
University, said Hillary Clinton has shed much of the carpetbagger
image in New York, but remains immutably linked to her husband, for
good or ill.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ''why shouldn't hubby come and help her? She helped
him plenty,'' Graff said. ''And Al Gore has now decided that the
most popular politician in America is Bill Clinton, and why
shouldn't he be attached to him?''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee, which doles out campaign cash
to Democratic candidates nationwide, hopes to raise $2 million at
Monday's event. Tony Bennett is the featured entertainment, with
political jokes and introductions by comic Jon Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The White House says it is only the first of several joint
appearances by the ''principals;'' Clinton, Gore, Mrs. Clinton and
Tipper Gore. All four are next slated to appear together on May 24
in Washington, at a DNC tribute to Clinton called the ''blue jean
bash.''
</P>
<P>
   The president has put in a couple of appearances at fund-raisers
for his wife's campaign, but a big-money Hollywood bash last
weekend was his first political appearance with Gore this year.
</P>
<P>
   The stepped-up money hunt partly reflects the rhythm of the
political season, which is speeding toward the party nominating
conventions this summer and the expensive television advertisements
and other national campaigning that will follow.
</P>
<P>
   The willingness of Gore and Mrs. Clinton to team up with the
president also reflects the fading of the impeachment and Monica
Lewinsky scandals and a recognition, says Columbia's Graff, that
Clinton remains a popular figure and adept fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are people in the Democratic Party who wish Bill Clinton
could run a third time,'' Graff said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope that doubling or tripling up the party's top
officeholders will draw more donors and energize party activists
and volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can't hurt,'' offered Siewert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
