<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Sparks SWAT Debate  </HEADLINE>
By COLLEEN SLEVIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Despite lawsuits claiming that faster
SWAT team action could have saved lives at Columbine High School,
experts say the specially trained officers won't change their slow,
methodical approach.
</P>
<P>
   What will change is the training for beat patrolmen, who are
being taught to act faster to control dangerous situations until
the SWAT teams arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some times when you need to rush into things,'' said
David Klinger, who is conducting a federally funded study of SWAT
operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, law enforcement leaders have been reluctant to send
ordinary patrolmen into tense situations because they have been
accused of being trigger happy, said Klinger, a criminologist at
the University of Missouri-St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many departments are training patrol officers to enter a
building immediately if shots are being fired -- as soon as they
have a team of four to provide 360 degrees of coverage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen lawsuits have been filed by the families of
the survivors and the 13 people killed after student gunmen Dylan
Klebold and Eric Harris opened fire at Columbine a year ago. Both
gunmen committed suicide during the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits accuse sheriff's deputies of acting too slowly; one
claims teacher Dave Sanders was left to bleed to death for more
than three hours while police waited to enter the school.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a bunch of cowards. They had guns, they had vests, they
had helmets, they should be prepared to go out and they might get
shot. These were 17- and 18-year-old kids in there,'' said Connie
Michalik, whose son, Richard, was paralyzed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff John Stone says the SWAT team members were heroes and
saved many lives with their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Glick, executive director of the National Tactical
Officers Association, thinks the victims' families need someone to
blame and, since the gunmen are dead, they are focusing on police.
</P>
<P>
   ''Officers are ready to lay their lives on the line,'' Glick
said. ''And they would have if they knew exactly where Dylan
Klebold and Eric Harris were.''
</P>
<P>
   There were too many unknowns when the SWAT officers first
entered the school, said Glick, who has interviewed many of the
officers who responded to the shootings at Columbine. They heard
screams and alarms but no gun shots. And after bombs were found in
backpacks the killers had dropped, every backpack became a
potential booby trap, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also were unsure of their targets. And they didn't know
if the school had plastic windows that could have deflected their
bullets, possibly toward students, said Commerce City Police Chief
Brian Hebbard, a former SWAT team commander who had members of his
team at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Glick said no one would have been helped if SWAT members had
recklessly exposed themselves to danger.
</P>
<P>
   ''When there's so much uncertainty, you move slowly and
methodically,'' Glick said. ''You don't just run past closed doors
and open doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Columbine, law enforcement agencies ran into obstacles
just trying to train SWAT teams. Klinger said many towns and
schools have refused to let them run drills.
</P>
<P>
   ''For 20 or 30 years, the message was 'don't think about it,
don't train for it,''' Klinger said. ''They thought it wouldn't
happen at their school. The problem is that it happens at
somebody's school and somebody dies because law enforcement hasn't
had the opportunity to do the practice it needs to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 1524 </TRAILER>
