<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Squatters Allowed To Stay  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Some 200 armed black squatters occupied
another white-owned farm, and police allowed them to stay Sunday,
while warning them not to use violence.
</P>
<P>
   Squatters and ruling party supporters have seized around 1,000
white-owned farms in what they say is a protest against unequal
land distribution, but what critics say is a bid by President
Robert Mugabe to rally supporters and intimidate opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The occupiers moved onto Lynton Farm Saturday afternoon and beat
and whipped some workers, said the cattle farm's owner, John
Malzer.
</P>
<P>
   Police visited the group of squatters early Sunday and told them
not to use violence. Malzer said he was disappointed that police
had allowed the squatters to stay, but that the visit had helped
calm an explosive situation.
</P>
<P>
   He remained in his home on the farm in the Marondera district,
40 miles east of Harare, saying he thought he was relatively safe.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, there was a standoff at a farm owned by the
Forresters family in Mvurwi district 60 miles north of Harare.
Squatters who had occupied the farm were preventing the owner's
wife from leaving her house and barring the farm owner from
entering, a neighbor said.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Minister Robin Cook said Sunday that other
southern African leaders had urged Mugabe to resolve the crisis
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said Mozambique's president, Joaquim Chissano, as well as
the president of South Africa and Namibia, had urged Mugabe at a
summit Friday to ensure that a Zimbabwean delegation takes a
positive stance in talks with the British government in London on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has said it is willing to resume funding to help
redistribute white-owned lands to landless blacks -- but only if
Mugabe ends the occupations.
</P>
<P>
   Two white farmers have been killed in the past two weeks, both
supporters of the opposition Movement for Democratic Change. Two
other MDC members, both black, were killed April 15, and several
farmers with opposition links have been beaten.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, an explosion went off outside Zimbabwe's only
independent daily newspaper, which has been sharply critical of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   State-controlled Zimbabwe Broadcasting Corp. reported Sunday
that the blast, which caused only light damage and no injuries, was
probably caused by a device hurled from a passing car.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the device, apparently a stun grenade, was
believed thrown from a Mazda 626 that was seen speeding away from
the scene after the blast, state radio and television reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police had no suspects in the bombing, spokesman Emmanuel
Chiwanda said.
</P>
<P>
   Two Daily News reporters visiting white-owned farms occupied by
illegal squatters were abducted and robbed earlier this month by
men claiming to be veterans of the bush war that led to Zimbabwe's
independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   After the reporters were released unharmed, Chenjerai Hunzvi,
head of the National Liberation War Veterans Association, argued
they were biased against Mugabe's ruling party. ''We hate The Daily
News,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunzvi's group claims to have led the occupation of the farms,
which began on Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has refused Supreme Court rulings ordering police to
remove the squatters, calling their actions a legitimate protest.
His opponents say he is allowing the occupations to shore up his
flagging popularity ahead of elections expected to be called in
May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 1528 </TRAILER>
