<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Battle For Jaffna  </HEADLINE>
By DILIP GANGULY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Sri Lankan government troops on Sunday
girded for what was expected to be a bloody battle for control of
Jaffna, a strategic stronghold that rebels are determined to
recapture.
</P>
<P>
   State-run radio in the capital of Colombo appealed to people to
donate blood, apparently fearing heavy casualties in the fight for
Jaffna, which the military captured from rebels five years ago. The
report said 500 people had already lined up to donate blood.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of fierce fighting, rebels on Saturday seized the
key Elephant Pass causeway in northern Sri Lanka -- the doorstep to
Jaffna. A 25-mile stretch of forest and rivers falls between the
pass and the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The military on Sunday sent reinforcements to Jaffna's airport,
which remains the only link with the mainland after the fall of the
causeway. Although Jaffna can be reached by ship, government
soldiers would be vulnerable to rebel artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
   A military officer said on condition of anonymity that
government troops withdrew from the Elephant Pass area after it
became clear that it would be very difficult to hold on. Troops
left through a narrow land corridor and headed toward Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   The officer said the military's biggest concern now was to stop
the rebels from moving their artillery closer to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam said it killed more than
1,000 soldiers in the two-day battle for the causeway. The Defense
Ministry said only 72 soldiers and seven officers were killed, and
625 were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   It also said more than 160 rebels died in the battle, including
12 who were killed Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Retaking Jaffna would be a huge morale boost for the rebels, who
are waging a 17-year-old war to set up an independent homeland for
minority Tamils. It would also give them an advantage in peace
talks being brokered by Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffna, 186 miles north of Colombo, remained cut off from the
mainland after telephone links were suspended to prevent the rebels
from establishing contacts with fighters believed to be hiding in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   A city of 500,000 people, Jaffna is the center of Tamil culture
and was the rebel capital until December 1995, when the military
captured the city. The defeat came as a huge blow to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The war, which began in 1983, has left more than 62,000 people
dead in this island nation near India's southern tip. The rebels
accuse the majority Sinhalese of discrimination against Tamils in
education and jobs, a charge the government denies.
</P>
<P>
   President Chandrika Kumaratunga was returning home from London,
where she went for a medical checkup. She was hurt in the eye
during a failed Tamil rebel assassination attempt in Colombo on
Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   In the Norwegian capital of Oslo, Tormod Endressen, a spokesman
for Norway's Foreign Ministry, confirmed the Tamil rebels had asked
the government to send a delegation to Sri Lanka. Endressen did not
say whether Oslo had agreed to the request.
</P>
<P>
   Norway began a peace initiative this year after both the Sri
Lankan government and Tamil Tiger rebels asked for help in
returning to the negotiating table after five years.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Rebel Web site: http://www.eelamweb.com
</P>
<P>
   Government Web site: http://www.priu.gov.lk
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 1545 </TRAILER>
