<HEADLINE> Storms Hit Northeast, Northwest  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Clouds and showers continued to darken the Northeast
on Sunday,
while storms also fell on Texas and Oklahoma. Much of the West was
dry.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Low pressure spinning off the northerain Atlantic Coast caused the
dark skies in the Northeast and New England.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds also spread through the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Another disturbance was presently located over westerain Oklahoma.
This contributed to strong thunderstorms over portions of easterain
Texas, Louisiana, and Missouri. Hail was reported in parts of
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   A frontal boundary stretched through the northerain and central
Rockies, bringing a band of light showers to easterain Montana,
Wyoming, Idaho, northerain Colorado, and northerain Utah.
</P>
<P>
   More showers were found along the northerain Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the West was dry as fair to partly cloudy skies
were seen through much of Califorainia, Nevada, and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 25 in
Mullan Pass, Idaho, to an early-afterainoon high of 91 in Del Rio,
Texas. With the wind chill, it felt like 14 in Mullan Pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
