<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Won't Use Old Spy Files  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder spoke out against
using old East German spy files in parliament's investigation into
the financial scandal surrounding the opposition Christian
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published Sunday in the Bild am Sonntag
newspaper, Schroeder also called on former Chancellor Helmut Kohl
to break his silence over the source of illegal campaign donations
that are at the center of the months-old scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time is ripe to adhere to the law and name the names of
the donors,'' Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl admitted in December having accepted some $1 million in
undeclared party donations in the 1990s, but has refused to reveal
the sources as required by law, insisting he gave his word to the
donors to keep them anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said it was up to the parliamentary committee
investigating the affair to decide whether to use recently surfaced
files kept by the communist secret police, known as the Stasi, on
Kohl and other prominent West German politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ''I don't think much of falling back on such
records.''
</P>
<P>
   Parliament is investigating allegations that money was traded
for political favors under Kohl's 16 years in office, something
Kohl has steadfastly denied.
</P>
<P>
   Some have speculated the Stasi files could help identify Kohl's
secret donors, but Volker Naumann, chairman of the investigative
committee, has said his panel will not use the material, including
transcripts of bugged conversations, because it was collected
illegally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
