<HEADLINE> Brazil Police Tactics To Be Probed  </HEADLINE>
By STAN LEHMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTO SEGURO, Brazil (AP) -- Federal prosecutors said Sunday they
would investigate the tactics used by police trying to quell
Indians protesting the celebration of the 500th anniversary of
Portugal's arrival in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Violent clashes between riot troopers and Indians protesting
what they called Portugal's ''invasion'' of this country erupted
Saturday at this seaside resort where Portuguese navigator Pedro
Alvares Cabral first made landfall on April 22, 1500.
</P>
<P>
   Police used clubs, tear gas and rubber bullets to break up a
crowd of about 2,000 Indians from all over Brazil who marched from
the nearby Coroa Vermelha reservation to join the protest. Many
Indians carried spears and banners in Portuguese reading ''500
years of resistance'' and ''Who said Brazil was discovered?''
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred protesters from black rights, student and labor
groups tried to join the Indians but were gassed and pushed back by
police, who had orders not to let them get near President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso, who was at the celebrations 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Police detained and later released 141 protesters, including 30
Catholic missionaries. According to unofficial reports, at least 15
people, mostly Indians, were injured during the clashes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Indians and their supporters were violently deprived of
their constitutional right of free expression,'' said federal
prosecutor Marcio Torres, who called the police approach
''heavy-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other federal prosecutors signed a note with Torres
criticizing the police action as ''illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The O Estado de Sao Paulo newspaper reported that an arrest
warrant had been issued for the police colonel who led the action
against the protesters. It was not possible to immediately confirm
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Minister for Institutional Security and Army General Alberto
Cardoso defended the police, saying they used ''adequate force to
prevent the demonstrators from marring the celebrations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
