<HEADLINE> Panama Faces U.S. Flag Decision  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY (AP) -- Months after the U.S. flag was lowered here
for the last time, Panama may allow the Stars and Stripes to fly
once again -- over a cemetery. But even that symbolic proposal faces
opposition, a nationalist group said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the executive branch sent a proposal to congress to
grant permission for the U.S. flag to fly over the canal-side
Corozal cemetery, which contains about 5,000 graves, mostly
American soldiers or U.S. citizens who helped build the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Movement for the Defense of Sovereignty said
the proposal would be a reminder of the nearly nine decades in
which the United States dominated the country.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is ''anti-nationalistic and promotes a painful colonial
enclave,'' the group said in a press statement. The proposal would
not involve U.S. control of the graveyard. The United States
lowered its last flag over the canal zone -- which it once
controlled -- in December.
</P>
<P>
   The plan still must be approved by Panama's legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
