<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Synagogue Attack Probed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERFURT, Germany (AP) -- Federal agents joined the investigation
Sunday into an attempted arson attack on a synagogue in eastern
Germany, the first such incident in Germany since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Saying they didn't have any suspects in the attack Thursday --
Adolf Hitler's birthday -- local authorities offered a $5,000 reward
for help in solving the crime. The synagogue is in Erfurt, the
capital of Thuringia state in former communist eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Local and federal investigators said they were looking closer
into a previously unknown group that claimed responsibility in a
letter found near the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   The note, which ended with ''Heil Hitler,'' was signed ''Die
Scheiteltraeger,'' or ''the side-part wearers,'' a reference to
Adolf Hitler's severe haircut that is usually used by leftists as
an insult for the far right.
</P>
<P>
   A leading ex-communist lawmaker in the Thuringia statehouse,
Bodo Ramelow, told police he received a threatening phone call
Saturday night from a man who identified himself as
''Scheiteltraeger.''
</P>
<P>
   Police would not release details of the call, but said they were
taking it ''very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramelow has been active in organizing demonstrations against the
far right in Thuringia, an economically depressed state of 2.5
million where unemployment reaches 20 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   He recently has been campaigning to block the annual May 1 march
by the far right National Party of Germany, to be held this year in
Weimar.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler's birthday was also marked in Sweden, where dozens of
neo-Nazis gathered in two cities in the south this weekend to mark
the day.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 neo-Nazis held a party Saturday night in the industrial
district of Helsingborg, 300 miles southwest of the capital,
Stockholm. Police did not intervene, and said participants came
from Sweden and Germany. The Swedish news agency TT reported that
some also came from Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Another 55 neo-Nazis carried torches and banners during a
10-minute march late Saturday through the center of Karlskrona,
also in southern Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was illegal because the marchers did not have
a permit, but police said they did not stop them because the march
was over so quickly and the demonstrators dispersed without
incident.
</P>
<P>
   A Molotov cocktail filled with diesel fuel was thrown at the
synagogue in Erfurt Thursday night, but the wick fell out on the
street and the flames were stamped out by a neighbor. The building,
built in 1952 to replace one destroyed by the Nazis, was undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   It was believed to be the first such attack in Germany since
neo-Nazis set a synagogue in Luebeck ablaze in 1994 and again in
1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 1714 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
