<HEADLINE> Devil Ray's Saunders Pitches  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Tony Saunders, the Tampa Bay pitcher
who broke a bone in his left arm last year, threw off a bullpen
mound Sunday for the second time in three days.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, we're just building strength,'' Saunders said after
his five-minute throwing session. ''Hopefully mine will come back
pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders fractured his left humerus -- the bone from the shoulder
to the elbow -- in a game against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got a stubborn personality, and in this situation that's
great,'' Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild said. ''He's made up
his mind he's going to pitch again and he's taken strides toward
that. He's set a goal and now he's going about accomplishing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Three other pitchers since 1989 -- Dave Dravecky, Tom Browning
and John Smiley -- have had similar injuries, but never fully
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first day I started throwing three months ago, I had to
forget about it,'' Saunders said. ''It's not something you can sit
there, think about and still throw.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no timetable for when Saunders will pitch in a game.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever it happens, it happens,'' Saunders said. ''If we set
a target date and I don't make it back, then I'll be mad, or
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders is currently on a schedule where he will throw off a
bullpen mound every other day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
