<DOCNO> APW20000423.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Princeton area, switching to new economy, is U.S. dot.com capital  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Albert Einstein's old stomping ground
doesn't get the same buzz -- or respect -- as Silicon Valley, yet
high-tech companies here are expanding so fast that competition for
the best workers has become cutthroat.
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton area now has more Internet domain names on a
per-capita basis than Boston, Silicon Valley or New York's Silicon
Alley, according to domain registrar Network Solutions. Companies
and individuals here have registered more than 4,750 domain names,
and government data shows nearly 1,200 high-tech companies or
business services were in Princeton and surrounding towns in 1997,
The Times of Trenton reported for Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies are poised to go public with the initial stock
offerings, about a dozen venture capital firms are based in
Princeton, and businesses that support those high-paying, high-tech
companies, such as law and accounting firms, are opening up nearby.
</P>
<P>
   It seems just one thing is missing.
</P>
<P>
   ''In New Jersey, we still don't have an AOL or Microsoft or
Apple, a name-brand technology company,'' Maxine Ballen, president
of the New Jersey Technology Council, told the newspaper. ''But I
really think it's just a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more successful firms, RCN Corp. of West Windsor,
buoyed by a recent $1.6 billion investment from Microsoft
co-founder Paul Allen, is scouting locations in nearby Lawrence and
Ewing townships for a bigger headquarters: about 1.5 million square
feet of space that could eventually employ 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Another West Windsor mainstay, Sarnoff Corp., which invented
color television, has been a trailblazer in commercializing
in-house research.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the past seven years, we've spun off 18 companies,'' 13 of
which have stayed here, Sarnoff spokesman Tom Lento said. ''We are
also starting an incubator that will focus on Internet-related
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that distinguishes the Route 1 corridor in central New
Jersey is the fact that executives of Internet startups and other
high-tech firms are more likely to be mature and experienced than
Silicon Valley entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Given the historically high salaries paid to top researchers in
company-sponsored facilities such as Sarnoff and Bell Labs, most
stayed put, said Jim Clingham. A 20-year Sarnoff veteran, he is now
guiding a handful of Internet startups.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of guys in their 50s like me who are getting
involved in startups,'' Clingham said. ''Up and down the Route 1
strip, people are coming to the conclusion that it's time to go it
on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Another difference from Silicon Valley, according to John
Martinson, chairman of a Lawrence venture capital firm called
Edison Venture Fund, is that the economy in Princeton's technology
corridor is less volatile than in other regions. That's partly
because of the high number of business service and health-care
firms that diversify the area's economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the corridor suffers from two problems: New Jersey's
perennial poor image and technology companies growing so fast they
have nearly exhausted the area's talent pool.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are now looking outside the state for qualified
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're using the Internet and sites like Monster and
HotJobs.com'' to find people, said Douglas Ford, Sarnoff's
personnel director. ''Workers are coming not only from other parts
of the country but also from overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state and private groups are trying to bring in
even more high-tech businesses and polish the area's image.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gov. Christie Whitman announced $165 million in
state, federal and private funds will be spent on work force
training, early funding for startups and upgrading the state's
Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   A Trenton-based nonprofit called Prosperity New Jersey will tout
the state as ''The Innovation Garden State'' in a marketing
campaign intended to attract out-of-state workers and even more
dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Jersey is really a high-tech powerhouse, and we really
need to do something to raise awareness of this,'' said Steven
Sasala, Prosperity's president. ''The only way we're going to do
that is to overcome the negative image of 'The Sopranos' and Jay
Leno jokes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
