<HEADLINE> Two Released in Border Graves Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Wrapping up an investigation into bodies
buried in clandestine graves along the U.S. border, prosecutors
have released the only two men arrested in the case from house
arrest, local media reported Sunday,
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and U.S. officials decided in January to end their joint
two-month excavation of suspected grave sites after turning up nine
bodies at three different sites. The dead are believed to be the
victims of drug-related violence,
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Reforma reported that the two men had been
released after 90 days' house arrest. They were identified as a
co-owner and caretaker of the La Campana ranch in the border city
of Ciudad Juarez where six of the bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's Office was unable to confirm the report
of their release.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man had been formally charged in the case, and both
claimed they had become involved with the property well after the
bodies -- some bound, gagged and executed -- had been buried there.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began Nov. 29 with 65 FBI agents and 600
Mexican military and federal judicial police, after a U.S.
government informant told authorities as many as 100 bodies might
be found at the ranch and three other sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
