<DOCNO> APW20000423.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miami Protests Said Handled Well  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN MEADOWS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The images were flashed around the world: Hour
after hour of police grabbing, sometimes beating protesters in the
streets of Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Rocks and bottles flying through the air. Smoke rising from
torched trash bins and tires. Police marching to the tap, tap, tap
of batons against acrylic shields and clouds of tear gas sprayed
into the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   A full-scale riot was the last thing Miami officers wanted over
the removal of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez from his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   They got their wish, but they still had to handle scores of
angry demonstrators and the aftermath of a federal raid most local
authorities knew very little about.
</P>
<P>
   And fresh in the minds of many were the scenes of police
grappling with protesters from Seattle to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Seattle demonstrators were able to block key
intersections and keep World Trade Organization delegates from
attending opening sessions. Police quickly lost control and
downtown Seattle suffered more than $2.5 million in damage and the
governor declared a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the District of Columbia prevented bands of
protesters from sabotaging world finance meetings, but still had
nasty street confrontations that led to more than 1,300 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, there were more than 350 arrests, but no serious
injuries. The problems tapered off Sunday morning and the streets
around the Little Havana home of Elian's relatives were quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Outside observers praised Miami police for their work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things could have been a lot worse,'' said Hubert Williams of
Police Foundation, a Washington D.C.-based nonprofit dedicated to
improving policing through better training and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''In spite of the high emotions, this thing did not get out of
hand. The police used pepper spray. They didn't use bullets,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami has suffered through its share of riots. Police learned
from the worst: The Liberty City riot of 1980, a Rodney King-like
response to a jury verdict over a confrontation between a black man
and police in which 18 people died.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Police Chief William O'Brien said in 1980, officers were
completely caught off guard and the result was lost lives and
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''The city absolutely burned, there was massive destruction of
property, massive looting. As a result we developed the plan we
worked under yesterday,'' O'Brien said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   During Saturday's protests, many on the street criticized the
police response as too heavy-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a corner amid clouds of tear gas, Martha Chisholm,
41, a Cuban born American, called the response a disgrace. She said
civil disobedience was a right police trampled.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel betrayed, we feel hurt,'' she said. ''It's a sad day
in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami Mayor Joe Carollo was also angry with the police chief,
saying he had ''lost all confidence'' in O'Brien for not notifying
the mayor or other city officials of the raid in advance.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien told The Miami Herald: ''This was a police issue, not a
political issue.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien and a handful of others were told of the raid Friday
afternoon. Despite the short notice, they were prepared after weeks
of anticipating trouble if federal agents took Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Brien said the world's view of Miami has been
tarnished. ''How many people do you think are booking trips to
Florida who haven't been here before?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-23-00 1758 </TRAILER>
