<HEADLINE> Lebanon Archbishop Criticizes Govt.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- A Lebanese archbishop criticized his
country's government and the Syrian press Sunday for claiming that
recent student protests against Syria were inspired by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Christian students demonstrated in Beirut last week, calling for
Syria to withdraw its 30,000 troops in Lebanon. Eight students were
arrested in clashes with riot police.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese President Emile Lahoud said Friday the protests served
Israeli interests. On Sunday, the Syrian state-run newspaper
Tishrin accused Israel of instigating the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a sign of deep weakness,'' Archbishop Elias Audi told
his congregation in a Palm Sunday sermon. The cleric's Eastern
Greek Orthodox Church celebrates Easter next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Audi said those judgments equated Lebanese protesters with
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we silence the university, who will speak out? The
ignorant?'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop, who rarely criticizes the government, did not
name Lahoud and the Syrian newspaper, but was clearly referring to
their statements.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has stationed troops in Lebanon as peacekeepers since
1976, a year after a Christian-Muslim civil war erupted. Lebanon's
pro-Syrian government says the Syrian military is a stabilizing
factor in the country's postwar recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But sections of the Christian community fear that Syria's
dominant role in Lebanon could be strengthened after Israel
withdraws its troops from south Lebanon, a pullout due to take
place by July.
</P>
</TEXT>
