<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Gas Prices Down Nearly 4 Cents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- The average price of gasoline in the
U.S. dropped nearly 4 cents a gallon at the pumps in the past two
weeks, the Lundberg Survey reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Lower crude oil prices and increased production were behind the
decline, analyst Trilby Lundberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The retail price cut speeded up the past two weeks. Lower
crude oil prices are the main cause, however, gasoline is also in
greater supply,'' Lundberg said after examining results of Friday's
survey of 10,000 gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices nationwide, including all grades and taxes, averaged
$1.532 per gallon, which was down 3.89 cents from the $1.5709
average on April 7. That was down 2.5 cents from the year's high of
$1.5958 on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a much bigger drop than last time and further gas
price cuts are more likely than not,'' Lundberg said, adding she
was still cautious about predicting pump price drops.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot predict the immediate future. There are contrary
trends at work,'' she said, referring to some fluctuation in crude
prices while production increases.
</P>
<P>
   The Camarillo-based Lundberg Survey showed the national average
price of gasoline, including taxes, at self-serve pumps was $1.4835
for regular, $1.5805 for mid-grade and $1.6643 for premium. At full
service pumps, the average was $1.8136 for regular, $1.910 for
mid-grade and $1.9776 for premium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
