<DOCNO> APW20000423.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnapped Colombia Athlete Released  </HEADLINE>
By JAIRO ANCHIQUE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's second-largest rebel group
released a national soccer star on Sunday, two days after
kidnapping him and violating a holiday truce.
</P>
<P>
   The National Liberation Army, or ELN, freed Andres Estrada in a
remote area of the turbulent western state of Antioquia. Estrada is
a former national team member and currently plays for the Atletica
National club in Medellin.
</P>
<P>
   At least 12 people were kidnapped over the weekend by a far
smaller leftist rebel faction when a landslide blocked holiday
traffic on a rural highway. Guerrillas from the 500-strong People's
Liberation Army, or EPL, snatched their victims from buses and
private cars 130 miles northeast of Bogota, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada, 32, said the rebels who seized him Friday night as he
was on a rural highway in his luxury car subsequently told him they
had erred in kidnapping him, but couldn't release him ''until they
received orders from their superiors.''
</P>
<P>
   The soccer star missed a Sunday afternoon game that didn't start
until his fellow athletes knew he was safe at home. They had all
signed a joint letter demanding Estrada's release.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada is the third major Colombian sports figure to be
kidnapped this year. Cycling stars Oliverio Rincon and Luis Herrera
were also seized, though Herrera was only kept one day.
</P>
<P>
   Leftist rebels often mount roadblocks on isolated country roads,
especially on holiday weekends, and charge ransoms for the release
of their victims. Colombia has the world's highest kidnapping rate.
</P>
<P>
   The ELN had declared an Easter week truce, giving holiday
travelers and commercial vehicles a break from harassment on the
nation's highways.
</P>
<P>
   The group, with an estimated 5,000 fighters, wants peace talks
with the government and last week freed eight hostages it had
seized in the April 12, 1999 kidnapping of an entire airline
flight. It still holds five people from that abduction.
</P>
<P>
   Though ELN commanders have said they would seek ransom for some
of the hostages, President Andres Pastrana was quoted in an
interview Sunday with the El Pais newspaper of Cali that no ransom
was paid in last week's releases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
