<HEADLINE> Sunday's Baseball Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees-Blue Jays:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Orlando Hernandez is the first four-game winner in the
American League. ... Bernie Williams' first-inning homer snapped a
2-for-20 skid. ... The 10 runs and 15 hits were both season highs
for the Yankees. ... The Yankees had a season high four home runs
against Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays have hit 41 home runs this month, one
short of a club record set in April 1996. ... The Blue Jays have
outhomered opponents 36-22 at SkyDome ... Brad Fullmer has 16 hits
and 15 RBIs in his last 31 at-bats. ... Toronto has hit
back-to-back homers four times this season. ... Jose Cruz Jr. hit
his eighth home run.
Angels-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Darin Erstad, who started the day as the AL batting
leader, went 1-for-3. He went 2-for-12 in the series and is hitting
.442. ... Troy Glaus went 0-for-4, snapping his career-high
nine-game hitting streak. ... The Angels went 4-6 on their first
road trip of the season. ... Manager Mike Scioscia said SS Gary
DiSarcina (thumb) will be activated from the disabled list Monday
and will be in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Bubba Trammell's two-run, game-winning home run
Saturday was his third homer and sixth hit in 12 career pinch-hit
at-bats. ''I just love to be up there with the game on the line,''
Trammell said. ''You shouldn't be here if you don't.'' ... On
Sunday, the Devil Rays wrapped up the first of three straight
three-game homestands. Their next three road trips are each
six-games long. ... Tampa Bay is 2-10 when scoring less than seven
runs.
Twins-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA-- Minnesota has won only four season series from Texas
over the past 12 years -- in 1988, 1993, 1996 and 1998. ... Entering
Sunday's game, Twins relievers were 2-0 with a 3.06 ERA and two
saves over their previous six games. Reliever Hector Carrasco
brought a 0.60 ERA into Sunday's game, having allowed no earned
runs over a stretch of four appearances and one earned run in nine
games.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-- Texas placed INF Frank Catalanotto on the DL following
and called up 3B Mike Lamb from Triple-A Oklahoma. Lamb was in
Sunday's starting lineup, making his major league debut. ... Lamb
was beaten out by Tom Evans in a training camp battle for the
starting job at third base. Lamb had seven errors in his first 12
games for Oklahoma. But with Evans hitting only .237 with no homers
and three RBIs in his first 16 games, the Rangers decided to give
Lamb another look. Lamb hit .255 with two homers and five RBIs in
14 games for Oklahoma.
Indians-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Because of four consecutive rainouts, Pedro Martinez
will go 10 days between outings. He said he doesn't like long
layoffs, noting that he injured himself last year, when he pitched
just two innings in the All-Star game during what was otherwise a
10-day layoff. ... 3B John Valentin is expected to fly to Florida
on Monday to begin rehabbing his left knee tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: The teams will play five games in three days Sept.
19-21 during what could be a September playoff race. Both teams are
9-6 after their lost weekend. ''You've got pennant races and
whatever going on then,'' pitcher Charles Nagy said. ''But that's
five months away.'' ... The rainouts protected Cleveland's six-game
road winning streak.
Tigers-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-- Tigers Manager Phil Garner said 2B Damion Easley would
see a hand specialist this week after preliminary X-rays revealed a
hairline crack in a bone in his right wrist. Easley was hit by a
pitch in Oakland on April 5 but the injury went undiagnosed until
now. Easley was placed on the 15-day DL retroactive to April 10
after suffering a strained ribcage muscle April 9 at Baltimore. ...
LHP Sean Runyan threw a perfect 1 1-3 innings of work in a rehab
appearance last night with Double-A Jacksonville. The 25-year-old
pitcher is trying to return from shoulder surgery. He is expected
to head to Triple-A Toledo this week for more work.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-- By going 5-for-5 Saturday, Chris Singleton became the
only player in baseball with three five-hit games over the past two
seasons. Singleton has raised his average more than 100 points in
the last five games. ... Newcomer Herbert Perry is ready. ''I
brought my boxing gloves,'' the ex-Devil Ray joked, referring to
Saturday's Chicago-Detroit brawl. Perry, who was activated Sunday
after being acquired of waivers from Tampa Bay, will be used at
third base against lefties, and will also see action at first base
and in the outfield. ''I just want to be in the big leagues,''
Perry said. ''Whatever job they have for me, I'll do.'' ... The
White Sox have been in first place for eight days, after having
spent a total of seven days on top of the AL Central over the
previous five seasons.
Royals-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: A bone scan revealed that Mariners' RHP Freddy Garcia
has a small hairline fracture in his right tibia and is expected to
miss 4-6 weeks. ... The Mariners started the season 7-2 at home for
the first time ever. ... Edgar Martinez has 801 career RBIs. He
joins Jay Buhner and Ken Griffey Jr. as the only Mariners to reach
that mark. ... Alex Rodriguez walked five times to move into the AL
lead with 18, and tie a team record.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals have had one other 0-9 road trip in team
history, June 27-July 6, 1986. ... In eight appearances against
Seattle, Jeff Suppan is 0-3 with 8.74 ERA. ... Going back to 1999,
the Royals have lost 14 of 16 on the road (2-11 in 2000).
Athletics-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: RHP Tim Hudson, who left his last start after getting
hit by a line drive on Thursday, threw in the bullpen before
Sunday's game and was pronounced healthy. He will take his regular
turn in the rotation on Tuesday against the Blue Jays. ... 2B Randy
Velarde went through a complete workout on Sunday and is getting
closer to beginning a rehab assignment. ''Any time you do enough
work to wear yourself out, it's a good sign,'' said A's trainer
Larry Davis. ... OF Matt Stairs is 1-for-18 against lefties.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: RHP Jose Mercedes said he used a different windup to
help him beat the A's on Friday and improve to 2-0 on the season.
''I was coming over the top, but I stayed down all day,'' said
Mercedes. ''I'm a sinkerball pitcher, but all my outs were
flyballs. That kind of surprised me.'' ... The Orioles have won
five of their first six series to date, including the Oakland
series. They didn't win their first series last year until April
30-May 2. ... Baltimore is 2-3 in one-run games.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Cubs-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Mark Grace was hitless in three at-bats against Mike
Hampton, leaving him 8-for-42 (.190) lifetime against the lefty.
... Reliever Ruben Quevedo gave up five runs while getting only two
outs, leaving him with a 27.00 ERA after five outings.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Reliever Pat Mahomes will start Monday's makeup game
against Los Angeles. He'll pitch in place of RHP Rick Reed, still
nursing a sore left thumb. ... The Mets' 15 runs were their most
since they beat Houston 17-1 last Aug. 30.
Brewers-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Jaime Navarro has lost all four starts this season.
Navarro has allowed 25 runs -- 21 earned -- in 16 1-3 innings for an
11.57 ERA. He has allowed 28 hits and 15 walks. ... The Brewers are
1-4 on their current nine-game road trip, Milwaukee's
second-longest trip of the season. ... Geoff Jenkins homered in all
three games of the series and had seven RBIs against the Expos.
Jenkins went 7-for-13 (.538) to raise his average from .264 to
.318. He leads the Brewers with seven homers and 14 RBIs. ...
Marquis Grissom has not grounded into a double play in 78 at-bats
this season.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Vladimir Guerrero went 2-for-3 with two RBIs to bring
him to within two RBIs of Henry Rodriguez's team record of 27 RBIs
in April, set in 1996. Guerrero, who has 99 career homers, is also
two homers short of Rodriguez's record of nine homers in April
1996. Guerrero leads the NL with 10 multi-hit games. Guerrero was
also walked intentionally -- with first base occupied -- during a
four-run rally in the Expos' 6-3 win Sunday. It was his major
league-leading sixth intentional walk. ... Tony Armas threw 80
pitches Saturday in a rehab outing for Class-A Jupiter. Armas, who
allowed three runs -- two earned -- and just one hit in 4 1-3
innings, is on the 15-day disabled list with tendinitis in his
right elbow. ... Closer Ugueth Urbina struck out the last four
batters he faced for his fifth save after allowing a run-scoring
single in the eighth. He has 14 strikeouts in nine innings. ...
Montreal has won six of its last eight home games to raise its
record to 10-8.
Phillies-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: The home runs by Brant Brown and Mike Lowell in the
first inning marked the first time the Marlins hit two homers in
one inning since Sept. 11, 1999 against Cincinnati. ... Injuries to
Luis Castillo and Dave Berg sped up the major league debut of Pablo
Ozuna, whom the Marlins acquired in December 1998 from the
Cardinals. Ozuna went 1-for-4. ... LF Cliff Floyd missed his second
consecutive game with a nagging groin pull. He hasn't started in
seven of the first 20 games. ... The Marlins extended their best
start ever to 12-8.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: 1B Rico Brogna was back in the starting lineup
after missing his first start of the season Saturday after being
hit in the knee with a pitch on Friday. ... The Phillies, who won
11 of 13 against Florida last season, are 1-2 this season. They're
1-5 on this seven-game road trip. ... The Phillies entered the game
with the major league lead in fielding percentage (four errors in
16 games) before committing two Sunday.
Dodgers-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Los Angeles is 1,000-973 against the Reds. The only
team with more wins over Cincinnati is San Francisco, which has
1,086. ... Kevin Brown, who broke the small finger on his right
hand while trying to bunt on April 8, threw without problem again
Sunday and is scheduled to return against Atlanta on Tuesday. ...
The eight-run sixth inning was the Dodgers' biggest since they
scored nine runs against Chicago on April 24, 1998. It was the
biggest inning allowed by the Reds since they gave up eight to the
Giants on July 24, 1998. ... Orel Hershiser, who tied the major
league record by hitting four Houston Astros on Wednesday, relieved
in the eighth and hit Aaron Boone.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: The Reds wore their all-red caps at home for the
first time since 1992 and went back to red sleeves for the first
time since the second game of the season.
Pirates-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Pittsburgh, which lost its eighth straight game at
Turner Field, is 1-11 in its last 12 games in Atlanta. ... Brian
Giles went 2-for-2 to boost his average to .400 (12-for-30) in his
last eight games. ... Walks are killing the Pirates, who issued
eight on Sunday. They dropped to 0-9 when walking four or more.
Starter Francisco Cordova and reliever Brad Clontz each issued a
pass that led to an Atlanta run. ... By losing 5-3 on Sunday, the
Pirates guaranteed themselves of a non-winning April for the fifth
straight year. In the homestand that begins Tuesday, Pittsburgh
would need six straight wins just to get to 12-12.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Braves manager Bobby Cox lists John Burkett as
day-to-day. The No. 5 starter, who left Saturday's game after three
innings with pain in his right shoulder, could land on the DL.
Regardless, Bruce Chen, who got the win after relieving Burkett,
will take his place in the rotation. ... Rudy Seanez, who pitched a
scoreless inning of relief for Greenville Saturday night, will make
another appearance Monday night for the Braves' Double-A affiliate.
''It feels a little sore,'' Seanez said Sunday. ''But you expect
that when you haven't been pitching much.'' The right-hander, who's
been nursing a strained muscle in his right side, hopes to be
activated from the DL during the upcoming home series against the
Dodgers. ... Steve Avery was roughed up for his second straight
outing in his minor-league rehabilitation stint. The left-hander
gave up six hits, four runs and three walks in 3 1-3 innings in a
start for Greenville on Saturday. Only one of the runs was earned.
Padres-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-- Houston right fielder Moises Alou returned to the
starting lineup Sunday. Alou had been limited to pinch hit duty the
last six days because of a strained right calf.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO-- Tony Gwynn needs one double to tie Ted Williams for
27th place on baseball's career list. Gwynn has 524 career doubles.
... The Astros are 2-6 at home. Only San Francisco (0-5) has a
worse home record. ... The Padres' staff leads the majors with 142
strikeouts.
Rockies-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Both of RHP Rick Croushore' victories have come
against the Cardinals, who traded him last offseason in the Darryl
Kile deal. ... Jose Jimenez, who went in the same trade, has saved
both of the Rockies' victories in the series. ... Just like last
season, Larry Walker is off to a slow home run start. He hit his
first on Sunday in Game 20. Last year he didn't hit his first until
April 28, when he belted three, and finished with 37. ... Jeff
Cirillo is 9-for-17 with four RBIs against Benes for his career.
Cirillo entered the day leading the NL with nine doubles, but he
has none the last six games. ... Neifi Perez is in a 2-for-18 slump
and Mike Lansing is 0-for-15. ... LHP Greg Myers has retired 11 of
the 14 lefties he's faced and has allowed only one of 11 inherited
runners to score.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Outfielder Jim Edmonds, among the league leaders in
batting (.386) and six other offensive categories, missed his
second straight start with a strained left foot although he entered
as a defensive substitute in center in the seventh. Edmonds started
the first 17 games for the Cardinals. ... Ray Lankford, 1-for-11
against left-handers and batting .167 overall, got the day off. ...
Manager Tony La Russa blamed Busch Stadium public address announcer
John Ulett for prematurely announcing LHP Rick Ankiel as a pinch
hitter in the sixth inning. La Russa was going to use Ankiel if
there was a runner on first, but he switched to Edmonds when J.D.
Drew walked and advanced on a groundout. ... Ankiel is 5-for-9 at
the plate with a home run, triple and two RBIs.
Giants-Diamondbacks:
</P>
<P>
   GIANTS: San Francisco swept the Diamondbacks for the first time.
The teams combined for a Bank One Ballpark-record 15 homers during
the three-game set. ... Jeff Kent finished the three-game series
6-for-15 with two homers and eight RBIs. He also robbed Tony Womack
of a hit in the sixth inning when he leaped high to catch a line
drive. ... Four of Bill Mueller's 20 career homers have come at
Arizona. ... Joe Nathan allowed seven of the first eight men he
faced to reach base safely. ... Barry Bonds, one of a handful of
Giants battling the flu, said he's feeling a little stronger but
still is extremely congested. Bonds went 3-for-5, including his
453rd career homer in the eighth inning. Bonds passed Carl
Yastrzemski for 21st place. ... San Francisco has scored 43 runs in
its 11 losses and 61 in its seven wins.
</P>
<P>
   DIAMONDBACKS: Luis Gonzalez hit his second homer in as many days
into the pool area in right-center field. His fifth-inning homer
was the 16th to land in the pool, the eighth by a Diamondback
hitter. ... Lenny Harris' eighth-inning pinch single was the 116th
pinch-hit of his career, tying him with Jerry Lynch for fifth place
on the career list. ... Arizona plays 18 of its next 24 games on
the road. ... Diamondback pitchers walked 17 batters in Arizona's
18 games, then walked 18 in the last three against San Francisco.
... C Damian Miller, who strained his hamstring running out a
double Saturday, was available for emergency duty but did not play.
Manager Buck Showalter said he will be re-evaluated Monday. ...
Brian Anderson's four-inning relief stint matched the team record
set April 5 by Mike Morgan.
</P>
