<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-23 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Boy Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A former anti-Castro guerrilla leader praised the
U.S. government Sunday for forcibly taking custody of Elian
Gonzalez, saying ''the showdown in Little Havana had to come to an
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Eloy Guiterrez-Menoyo, who spent 22 years in Cuban prisons for
trying to start an uprising against Fidel Castro, issued a
statement saying Elian's Miami relatives ''misread the patience of
the government'' and ''acted with defiance'' in refusing to reunite
the boy with his father.
</P>
<P>
   As leader of the group Cambio Cubano, or Cuban Change,
Guiterrez-Menoyo has often clashed with Miami's other Cuban exile
groups suspicious of his support for working with the Cuban
government toward democratic reform. His views on the Elian drama
put him at similar odds.
</P>
<P>
   He said the group recognizes the ''paternal rights'' of Elian's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez. But he urged the Cuban government
against using the boy as ''a flag in an attempt to hide behind it
the enormous failings of the Cuban system.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
News photographer charged with throwing rocks at police
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Four news photographers were among the hundreds
arrested in the Little Havana protests, including a woman working
for the Los Angeles Times who police said threw several rocks at
police and then photographed the action.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Cole, 38, was arrested on felony charges of throwing
deadly missiles, Miami Police Det. Delrish Moss said Sunday. She
faces up to five years if convicted, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cole ''was seen throwing two or three rocks and then picked up
her camera and proceeded to take photographs,'' Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   Times Editor Michael Parks said Sunday that the newspaper is
seeking immediate dismissal of the charge against Cole.
</P>
<P>
   ''Carolyn Cole was covering the protests in Miami as a news
photographer, not participating in them, and her photographs
published in the Times make that clear,'' Parks said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''In arresting Cole and detaining her for more than eight hours
before releasing her on bond, Miami police prevented her from
continuing to report a story of national importance,'' Parks said.
''We see this as an abridgment of the people's right to know under
the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   A photo by Cole appeared on the front page of Sunday's paper,
and several ran inside. The paper also reported her arrest at the
end of a longer article.
</P>
<P>
   Moss said three other photographers were arrested on charges
that ranged from misdemeanor charges of disorderly conduct to a
felony charge of battery on a police officer. He did not have
confirmation of the news outlets they worked for.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Sen. Bob Graham criticizes federal raid
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Law enforcement officials should have known they
did not need machine guns and tear gas to seize Elian Gonzalez from
the home of his Miami relatives, Sen. Bob Graham said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If law enforcement's intelligence didn't know what was
happening in that little house right in back of us for five months,
didn't have an absolute 100 percent understanding ... there was a
mammoth failure of law enforcement intelligence,'' said Graham, a
Miami Democrat and former two-term Florida governor.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, standing in front of the home of the 6-year-old boy's
Miami relatives in Little Havana, told ABC's ''This Week'' that
President Clinton assured him three weeks ago that federal agents
would not attempt to seize Elian at night.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have defended the use of force, saying they did
not know whether there were weapons in the home or what kind of
resistance agents might encounter. Armed agents snatched the boy
before dawn and whisked him to a reunion with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Miami Herald prints front-page editorial
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Herald took to its front page to call for
an independent investigation into the need for an armed raid to
take custody of Elian Gonzalez. The paper also urged the community
to stay calm.
</P>
<P>
   The unsigned opinion piece, appearing at the bottom of a front
page devoted entirely to the drama, said Elian's Miami relatives
appeared to be close to a deal to reunite the boy with his father
when Attorney General Janet Reno ordered the raid.
</P>
<P>
   ''Miami needs a complete accounting of the events preceding the
raid,'' the editorial said. ''The scenes of overwhelming force from
yesterday at dawn shock the conscience. A separate question is
whether the raid was even necessary or was a betrayal of those who
were on the verge of achieving a peaceful transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said a ''full and independent investigation of
this matter is warranted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
